textAfterTable: 12 Titel Albenrezension It would be easy to dismiss the Puerto Rican quartet Da' Zoo as mere Black Eyed Peas imitators with a Latin lilt. Granted, they do share a similar lineup (a couple rapper/singers and a girl to sing the hooks), a similarly slick and totally Pop-with R&B additives-musical approach, and write the same kind of songs that (usually) hit the spot right between naggingly catchy and completely nagging that the BEP specialize in. What Da' Zoo add to the BEP's formula on their self-titled debut album is a Day-Glo™ sense of fun and frolic that places the band closer to LEN or Fannypack on the easygoing good-times spectrum. They sound like they are having fun making the music instead of working hard so that you will have fun listening to it. That's a trap that snares many pop projects, but not Da' Zoo. They romp through frothy jams ("Cuchi Cuchi," "Ponte Ready"), teen pop love songs ("TU," "Chitu") and joyous pop/rockers (the positively giddy "Pajamas") like goofy kids without a care in the world. Even the ballads like "Otro Love" and "Cerce de Mi" have a bounce to them that keeps things light and enjoyable.
